---
import Doc from '../layouts/Doc.astro';
import CopyableCode from '../components/CopyableCode.astro';

const config = `{
  "mcpServers": {
    "leji": { "command": "npx", "args": ["-y", "@leji-org/mcp"] }
  }
}`;

const resources = [
   ['leji://spec/full', 'The complete specification, one document.'],
   ['leji://spec/{id}', 'One spec document, e.g. leji://spec/conformance.'],
   ['leji://schema/{name}', 'One JSON Schema, e.g. leji://schema/context-manifest.'],
   ['leji://cli/help', 'The leji CLI command and option reference.'],
];

const tools = [
   ['search_spec', 'Spec sections matching a query.'],
   ['fetch_spec_doc', 'One spec document (or the whole spec).'],
   ['fetch_schema', 'One JSON Schema.'],
   ['validate_manifest', 'Validate a leji.json supplied inline.'],
   ['validate_layer', 'Validate the context layer at a path.'],
   ['score_conformance', 'Claimed vs verified conformance level.'],
   ['explain_conformance', 'What is verified, and what the next level needs.'],
];
---

<Doc
   title="MCP server · Leji"
   description="Use Leji tooling from your AI agent: a local, read-only Model Context Protocol (MCP) server that serves the spec and schemas and validates and scores a context layer on your disk. Install once, no shell required."
>
   <h1>MCP server</h1>
   <p class="sp-lede">
      Leji's tooling comes in two ways. The <a href="/cli/">CLI</a> is for you and your CI; the Model Context Protocol (MCP)
      server is for your agent.
   </p>
   <p>
      <code>@leji-org/mcp</code> is a local <a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
         >MCP</a
      > server that wraps the reference SDK. Your agent reads the spec and schemas and runs validation and conformance against
      a context layer on disk, instead of reading this site and shelling out to the CLI. It runs locally over stdio, needs
      no network or auth, and exposes only read-only tools.
   </p>

   <h2>Add it to your client</h2>
   <p>
      Configure it once in any MCP client (Claude Code, Claude Desktop, Cursor, Windsurf, and others). The client
      launches
      <code>leji-mcp</code> on demand; the <code>leji</code> tools then appear in every session, in every repo, with no further
      setup.
   </p>
   <CopyableCode code={config} lang="json" label="Copy MCP config" />
   <p>
      Requires <a href="https://nodejs.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Node.js</a> 22 or newer (<code>npx</code> ships
      with Node). The first run fetches the package; later runs use the cache.
   </p>
   <p>Point each tool at the repository root that holds your <code>leji.json</code>.</p>

   <h2>Tools</h2>
   <p>All read-only. Nothing the server exposes can write or change your layer.</p>
   <table class="mcp-table">
      <tbody>
         {
            tools.map(([name, summary]) => (
               <tr>
                  <td>
                     <code>{name}</code>
                  </td>
                  <td>{summary}</td>
               </tr>
            ))
         }
      </tbody>
   </table>

   <h2>Resources</h2>
   <table class="mcp-table">
      <tbody>
         {
            resources.map(([uri, summary]) => (
               <tr>
                  <td>
                     <code>{uri}</code>
                  </td>
                  <td>{summary}</td>
               </tr>
            ))
         }
      </tbody>
   </table>

   <h2>Why a server, and not just the CLI?</h2>
   <p>
      The CLI already validates and scores a layer. The server adds no new capability; it's a different surface, the one
      an agent reaches for on its own:
   </p>
   <ul>
      <li>
         <strong>It's self-advertised.</strong> Configured once, it shows up in your agent's tool list every session, with
         descriptions of exactly what it does. Nobody has to tell the agent that Leji exists or where to find the CLI.
      </li>
      <li>
         <strong>It works where a shell doesn't.</strong> Many agent environments can't or won't run arbitrary commands. A
         read-only server with no network is reachable where <code>leji validate</code> is not.
      </li>
      <li>
         <strong>It serves the spec and schemas directly.</strong> Your agent reads them as resources, without a web fetch,
         and cites them as it works.
      </li>
   </ul>
   <p>
      Consuming a layer doesn't need the server: a conformant repository's <a href="/spec/boot-profile/">boot profile</a
      > already onboards your agent. The server is for the other half, building, validating, and learning Leji.
   </p>
</Doc>

<style>
   .mcp-table {
      width: 100%;
      border-collapse: collapse;
      margin: 0.8rem 0 0;
   }
   .mcp-table td {
      padding: 0.5rem 0.9rem 0.5rem 0;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
      vertical-align: top;
      color: var(--ink-soft);
   }
   .mcp-table td:first-child {
      white-space: nowrap;
   }
   .mcp-table td code {
      color: var(--blue-deep);
      font-size: 0.85em;
   }
</style>
